<h4><a id="user-content-the-illustrated-man-1951-by-ray-bradbury-41-" class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" href="#the-illustrated-man-1951-by-ray-bradbury-41-"><svg class="octicon octicon-link" viewBox="0 0 16 16" version="1.1" width="16" height="16" aria-hidden="true"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24830.The_Illustrated_Man" rel="nofollow">The Illustrated Man</a> (1951) <em>by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Bradbury" rel="nofollow">Ray Bradbury</a></em> [4.1] <g-emoji class="g-emoji" alias="star2" fallback-src="https://assets-cdn.github.com/images/icons/emoji/unicode/1f31f.png">ðŸŒŸ</g-emoji></h4>
<blockquote>
<p>That <em>The Illustrated Man</em> has remained in print since being published in 1951 is fair testimony to the universal appeal of Ray Bradburyâ€™s work. Only his second collection (the first was <em>Dark Carnival</em>, later reworked into <em>The October Country</em>), it is a marvelous, if mostly dark, quilt of science fiction, fantasy, and horror. In an ingenious framework to open and close the book, Bradbury presents himself as a nameless narrator who meets the Illustrated Manâ€”a wanderer whose entire body is a living canvas of exotic tattoos. Whatâ€™s even more remarkable, and increasingly disturbing, is that the illustrations are themselves magically alive, and each proceeds to unfold its own story, such as â€œThe Veldt,â€ wherein rowdy children take a game of virtual reality way over the edge. Or â€œKaleidoscope,â€ a heartbreaking portrait of stranded astronauts about to reenter our atmosphereâ€”without the benefit of a spaceship. Or â€œZero Hour,â€ in which invading aliens have discovered a most logical allyâ€”our own children. Even though most were written in the 1940s and 1950s, these 18 classic stories will be just as chillingly effective 50 years from now. â€”Stanley Wiater</p>
</blockquote>
